          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily programming across 4 testers</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Steelcase Gesture</strong> is the most adjustable office chair we have tested in 2026. The armrests move in every direction anyone could want, the 3D LiveBack flexes with your spine through every posture, and the 12-year warranty means it will outlast most desks. At $999 it is expensive and the design is corporate — but for programmers and heavy computer users, no chair matches the Gesture's combination of support and adjustability.
      </div>

      <p>Steelcase launched the Gesture in 2013, designed around a study of how people actually sit while using phones, tablets, and laptops — not the upright posture that older chairs assumed. The Gesture has been updated since, but the core idea holds: a chair that supports you whether you are typing, reclining, swiping on a phone, or leaning back on a call. We bought the Gesture at retail and put it through 60 days of daily programming, including 10-hour sessions, reclined code reviews, and shared use by four testers ranging from 5'4" to 6'3".</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against the Leap V2, the Herman Miller Aeron, and budget alternatives, see our <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">ergonomic chair roundup</a>. If you want the Gesture's sibling for $300 less, our <a href="/reviews/steelcase-leap-v2-review/">Steelcase Leap V2 review</a> covers the differences in detail.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Armrests: The Reason to Buy the Gesture</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of the Gesture is its armrests. They are not just adjustable — they are the most adjustable armrests on any chair we have tested. Each armrest moves in five dimensions: height (4 inches of travel), width (in and out from the seat), depth (forward and back), pivot (left and right angle), and 360° rotation. No other chair, including the Herman Miller Aeron and the Leap V2, offers this range of motion.</p>

      <p>In practice, this means the armrests meet your arms wherever they are. Typing? Set them low and narrow. Reclined on a call? Rotate them inward and raise them to support your forearms. Reading on a phone? Pivot them out and rest your elbows wide. We spent the first day dialing in our preferred upright position, then discovered we could shift to a reclined reading position in seconds by adjusting both armrests simultaneously.</p>

      <p>The armrest pads are a soft polyurethane that is grippy enough to hold your arms in place without sticking to bare skin. They are replaceable — a set costs about $40 — and they show no wear after 60 days of heavy use. The only complaint is that the armrests are so adjustable that a first-time user needs 30 minutes to dial them in correctly. Once set, they stay put, but the initial setup is a real investment.</p>

      <h3>3D LiveBack: A Back That Flexes With You</h3>
      <p>The Gesture's backrest uses Steelcase's 3D LiveBack technology — a flexible shell with embedded flexors that move with your spine as you change posture. Unlike a rigid backrest that forces you into one position, the LiveBack flexes laterally and vertically, so reclining, leaning, and twisting all feel supported rather than fought.</p>

      <p>The difference is most noticeable when you recline. On a rigid chair, reclining lifts your feet off the floor and strains your lower back. On the Gesture, the backrest flexes backward while the seat pan tilts forward slightly, keeping your feet planted and your spine supported through the full range of motion. We reclined to a near-horizontal position for code reviews and felt no pressure points across our back.</p>

      <p>The backrest also adjusts in height — about 4.5 inches of travel — so the lumbar support lands in the right spot regardless of your torso length. Our 5'4" tester and our 6'3" tester both found a comfortable position within a minute of adjustment. The lumbar is not separately adjustable (it moves with the backrest), but the flex of the LiveBack distributes pressure evenly enough that we did not miss a dedicated lumbar dial.</p>

      <h3>Seat Pan and Weight Capacity: Fits Everyone</h3>
      <p>The seat pan comes in two sizes: standard (19" wide, 19" deep) and plus (22" wide, 20.5" deep). The standard seat is wider than most chairs at this price, and the seat depth adjusts forward and back by about 2 inches — enough to fit shorter users who need a shallower seat and taller users who need more thigh support. The Gesture is rated for users up to 400 lbs on the standard base, and 500 lbs on the plus base.</p>

      <p>The seat foam is Steelcase's default 4.5-density foam — supportive but not plush. If you want a softer cushion, the Gesture is not the right chair; consider the Leap V2, which has a slightly softer seat, or a cushioned chair like the Branch Ergonomic. After 60 days, our testers were split on the cushion: the heavier testers (200+ lbs) loved the firm support; the lighter testers found it slightly hard for the first week before the foam broke in.</p>

      <p>The seat glides smoothly on a steel base that does not wobble, even when fully reclined. The pneumatic height adjustment moves through 4.5 inches of travel, accommodating users from about 5'0" to 6'5". We tested the Gesture with users at the extremes of that range and all found a comfortable seat height within seconds.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality: 47 lbs of Steel and Engineered Plastic</h3>
      <p>The Gesture weighs 47 lbs — about twice the weight of a budget office chair. The heft comes from a steel base, a steel mechanism, and a reinforced shell. The result is a chair with no creaks, no flex, and no wobble. Squeeze the armrests, lean hard into the backrest, or rock the chair side to side — nothing moves that should not move.</p>

      <p>The weight is a feature for stability, but a drawback for portability. Moving the Gesture between rooms is a real workout, and it is not a chair you will casually carry upstairs. Once it is in place, though, the weight is an asset. The chair stays planted when you recline, the casters roll smoothly on a hard floor or a desk pad, and the mechanism feels as solid on day 60 as it did on day 1.</p>

      <p>The fit and finish are excellent. The fabric is tight with no bunching, the stitching is even, and the plastic shells have no mold lines or sharp edges. Our test chair came in the default black fabric with a black frame — a corporate look that disappears in an office but would not be our first choice for a home studio. Steelcase offers dozens of fabric and color options, but premium fabrics add $150 to $400 quickly.</p>

      <h3>12-Year Warranty: Buy It for Life</h3>
      <p>The Gesture ships with a 12-year warranty that covers parts, foam, and fabric — the longest coverage in the office chair industry alongside Herman Miller. In practice, this means Steelcase will replace any failed component for over a decade, and the chair is serviceable by Steelcase technicians if a major component fails.</p>

      <p>This is the core value proposition of a $999 chair. A $300 ergonomic chair lasts three to five years before the foam compresses, the mechanism loosens, or the fabric tears. The Gesture lasts 15 to 20 years with the same level of daily use. Over 12 years, the Gesture costs about $83 per year — cheaper than replacing a $300 chair every three years, and the experience is incomparably better.</p>

      <p>We have spoken to users with 10-year-old Gestures that still feel new. The foam retains its density, the mechanism is tight, and the fabric shows only minor wear. If you sit for a living and plan to keep the chair for a decade, the warranty alone justifies the price premium over a budget chair.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested the Gesture against three competing chairs at different price points. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Chair</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Armrests</th>
            <th>Back</th>
            <th>Weight Cap</th>
            <th>Warranty</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Steelcase Gesture</strong></td>
            <td>$999</td>
            <td>5D + rotation</td>
            <td>3D LiveBack</td>
            <td>400 lbs</td>
            <td>12 years</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Steelcase Leap V2</td>
            <td>$679</td>
            <td>4D</td>
            <td>LiveBack</td>
            <td>500 lbs</td>
            <td>12 years</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Herman Miller Aeron</td>
            <td>$1,395</td>
            <td>4D</td>
            <td>Mesh</td>
            <td>350 lbs</td>
            <td>12 years</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Branch Ergonomic</td>
            <td>$329</td>
            <td>3D</td>
            <td>Cushion</td>
            <td>275 lbs</td>
            <td>5 years</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Steelcase Leap V2</strong> is the Gesture's sibling and the value pick of the Steelcase lineup. It shares the 12-year warranty and a similar LiveBack design, but the armrests are 4D (no rotation) and the backrest is less flexible. For $300 less, the Leap V2 is the right pick if you do not need the Gesture's armrest range. See our <a href="/reviews/steelcase-leap-v2-review/">Leap V2 review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Herman Miller Aeron</strong> is the iconic mesh chair — firmer, cooler, and more design-forward than the Gesture. The Aeron wins on breathability (no cushion to trap heat) and aesthetics. The Gesture wins on armrest adjustability, cushion comfort, and fitting a wider range of body types. If you run hot or want a chair that looks as good as it functions, the Aeron is the pick. See our <a href="/reviews/herman-miller-aeron-review/">Aeron review</a> for details.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Branch Ergonomic</strong> at $329 is the budget champion — adjustable armrests, decent lumbar support, and a mesh back. It is not in the same league as the Gesture for build quality or adjustability, but for a third of the price it is a real value. If your budget tops out at $400, see our <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-under-500/">best ergonomic chair under $500</a> roundup.</p>

      <p>Pair the Gesture with a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-home-office/">standing desk</a> for a sit-stand workflow — the Gesture's smooth casters and stable base make it ideal for transitioning between sitting and standing. Add a <a href="/reviews/best-foot-rest-desk/">foot rest</a> to complete the ergonomic chain.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Gesture if you sit for a living and plan to keep the chair for a decade. The 12-year warranty, the best-in-class armrests, and the 3D LiveBack deliver an ergonomic experience that no sub-$500 chair can match. Programmers, writers, and analysts who spend 8+ hours a day in a chair are the target audience.</p>

      <p>Get the headrest if you recline often. The $150 headrest upgrade is worth it for code reviews, video calls, and reading. If you sit upright all day, skip it — the headrest is unnecessary and can get in the way of standing up quickly.</p>

      <p>Skip the premium fabrics unless aesthetics matter. The default fabric is durable and breathes fine. Premium fabrics (leather, wool) add $200 to $400 and are a luxury, not a necessity. Save the money for a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-home-office/">standing desk</a> instead.</p>

      <p>Buy from a Steelcase dealer, not a random reseller. Authorized dealers honor the full 12-year warranty; gray-market chairs often come with no warranty or a 1-year warranty. The price difference is usually small, and the warranty is the entire point of buying a Gesture.</p>

      <p>Consider the Leap V2 instead if the Gesture is out of budget. The Leap V2 costs $679, shares the 12-year warranty, and offers 90% of the Gesture's ergonomics for 68% of the price. The only meaningful losses are armrest rotation and backrest flex. For most users, the Leap V2 is the smarter buy — see our <a href="/reviews/steelcase-leap-v2-review/">Leap V2 review</a>.</p>

      <p>Avoid the Gesture if you want a soft, sink-in cushion. The Gesture prioritizes support over plushness. If you want a softer seat, the Leap V2 or a cushioned chair like the Branch Ergonomic is the better fit. If you run hot, consider the <a href="/reviews/herman-miller-aeron-review/">Herman Miller Aeron</a> with its breathable mesh.</p>

